---
import { getCollection } from "astro:content";
import BaseLayout from "../components/layout/BaseLayout.astro";

const REPO = "https://github.com/coderturtle/borrow-native";
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;

const recentEntries = (await getCollection("buildlog", ({ data }) => !data.draft))
  .sort((a, b) => b.data.pubDate.valueOf() - a.data.pubDate.valueOf())
  .slice(0, 3);
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Borrow Native: guide"
  description="Learn Rust the way you already work, with your agent, and let the compiler be the first gate."
>
  <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold">Borrow Native</h1>
  <p class="mt-2 text-lg opacity-80">
    Learn Rust the way you already work, with your agent, and let the compiler, not an opinion, be the first gate.
  </p>

  <div class="post-body mt-10">
    <p>
      This page is the guide for anyone landing on the deployed site rather than the repo
      directly. The workshop itself, seven modules covering ownership through concurrency plus a
      synthesis capstone, lives in the <a href={REPO}>repo</a>, whose own README covers the same
      ground in more detail once you've cloned it. Nothing here substitutes for cloning it; this
      is orientation, not the content.
    </p>

    <h2>Two gates, not one</h2>
    <p>
      Every exercise runs through your own coding-agent harness (Claude Code, Codex, or
      equivalent). A <strong>deterministic gate</strong> checks first: <code>cargo test</code>{" "}
      green, <code>cargo clippy</code> clean, no judgment call. Then a{" "}
      <strong>conceptual gate</strong>: Coachgremlin, this workshop's teaching agent (a role you
      run yourself, inside your own harness, not a hosted service), checks whether you worked
      with the borrow checker or just found a way around it. A green compiler is necessary,
      never sufficient on its own.
    </p>

    <h2>Rust already has great teaching material. This isn't a replacement for it.</h2>
    <p>
      The official Rust Book, Rustlings, and Exercism already teach this language well. Borrow
      Native's arc is anchored to them, not built to replace them; what it adds is delivery
      through your own agent, a deterministic-plus-conceptual gate instead of a bare pass/fail,
      and a keepable takeaway per module. See the repo's{" "}
      <code>docs/workshop-design.md</code> for the full curriculum-anchor research.
    </p>

    <h2>What you walk away with</h2>
    <p>
      Two different things get built during each module: your own judgment, and a reusable
      artifact your agent can load next time. See each module's own README (once authored) for
      the evidence behind its specific gate.
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>You</strong> get practiced judgment: reading a borrow-checker error and finding
        the real fix instead of a workaround, modeling data so illegal states are
        unrepresentable, and diagnosing which concept is actually the bottleneck when something
        doesn't compile or doesn't feel idiomatic.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Your agent</strong> gets the packaged takeaways: a move-error diagnostic
        checklist, a borrow-checker playbook, an idiomatic-modeling checklist, a
        trait-bound/lifetime cheat-sheet, a custom-error-type template, a concurrency decision
        guide, and a personal Rust diagnostic playbook tying it all together.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h2>The runbook</h2>
    <ol>
      <li>
        Prerequisites: comfortable with git, the CLI, and reading a diff; general programming
        fluency in another language; already using a coding-agent harness regularly; Rust and
        <code>cargo</code> installed.
      </li>
      <li>
        Clone it: <code>git clone {REPO}.git</code>
      </li>
      <li>
        Start at <code>modules/README.md</code>. It has the full arc, in order, and a table of
        what each module's gate requires and what you keep from it.
      </li>
      <li>
        Work through the seven modules in order: ownership, borrowing, structs/enums,
        generics/traits/lifetimes, error handling, concurrency, then the synthesis capstone. Each
        states a hard prerequisite on an earlier one.
      </li>
      <li>
        No module completes by reading it. Every module states a required gate, checked first
        mechanically, then conceptually. If a module ever reduces to "read this, then move on,"
        or a link here is broken, that's a defect: <a href={`${REPO}/issues`}>open an issue</a>.
      </li>
    </ol>
  </div>

  {
    recentEntries.length > 0 && (
      <>
        <h2 class="mt-14 text-xl font-semibold">Recent from the build log</h2>
        <ul class="mt-6 space-y-4">
          {recentEntries.map((entry) => (
            <li>
              <a href={`${base}build-log/${entry.id}/`} class="entry-card">
                <p class="entry-title text-lg font-semibold">{entry.data.title}</p>
                <p class="mt-1 text-sm opacity-80">{entry.data.description}</p>
              </a>
            </li>
          ))}
        </ul>
        <p class="mt-6 text-sm opacity-70">
          See the <a href={`${base}build-log/`} class="underline">full index</a>.
        </p>
      </>
    )
  }
</BaseLayout>
